Most likely the failing test is because `AuthService` now has a new constructor dependency:

```java
private final ArthurSecurityProperties arthurSecurityProperties;
```

So your `@InjectMocks AuthService authService;` test now needs a mock or real instance.

Use a real properties object in the test.

```java
@Mock
private PartnerRepositoryClient partnerRepositoryClient;

@Mock
private OidcDiscoveryClient oidcDiscoveryClient;

@Mock
private RandomValueGenerator randomValueGenerator;

@Mock
private PkceService pkceService;

@Mock
private RedisAuthTransactionService redisAuthTransactionService;

@Mock
private RedisLoginHandoffService redisLoginHandoffService;

@Mock
private WebClient webClient;

@Mock
private JwtService jwtService;

@Mock
private RedisSessionService redisSessionService;

private ArthurSecurityProperties arthurSecurityProperties;

private AuthService authService;

@BeforeEach
void setUp() {
    arthurSecurityProperties = new ArthurSecurityProperties();

    authService = new AuthService(
            partnerRepositoryClient,
            oidcDiscoveryClient,
            randomValueGenerator,
            pkceService,
            redisAuthTransactionService,
            redisLoginHandoffService,
            webClient,
            jwtService,
            redisSessionService,
            arthurSecurityProperties
    );
}
```

Then remove:

```java
@InjectMocks
private AuthService authService;
```

Also add this import:

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach;
```

If your constructor order is different, follow the exact order from `AuthService` fields.

In your sales-point test, now the handoff expiry uses:

```java
arthurSecurityProperties.getHandoff().getTtlSeconds()
```

So this real object gives default value:

```java
60
```

and the test should pass again.
